<title>UK: UK independent forecasts show year-end rates at 7%.</title>
<headline>UK independent forecasts show year-end rates at 7%.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-06-16</dateline>
<text>
<p>Official British interest rates are expected to rise to about seven percent in the fourth quarter of 1997 from 6.5 percent at present, according to the latest summary of new independent forecasts compiled by the Treasury.</p>
<p>The survey of 31 new forecasts by economists in the City and other institutions produced an average forecast of 6.95 percent for base rates in the last quarter of this year, rising to 7.19 percent in Q4 1998.</p>
<p>Underlying inflation, excluding mortgage interest payments, is expected to hit the government's target of 2.5 percent late this year but is tipped to rise to 3.1 percent by the end of 1998.</p>
<p>Following are key forecasts from the Treasury compilation (annual percentage changes unless otherwise stated):</p>
<p>AVERAGE OF NEW FORECASTS</p>
<p>							   1997	  1998</p>
<p>    GDP						  3.4	   2.8</p>
<p>    RPI						  2.9	   3.3</p>
<p>    RPIX (Q4)					  2.5	   3.1</p>
<p>    Unemployment (Q4, millions)		  1.52	  1.38</p>
<p>    Current account deficit (billion stg)    4.3	   8.9</p>
<p>    PSBR (billion stg)			    16.2	  11.6</p>
<p>    Interest rates (Q4)			    6.95	  7.19</p>
<p>NOTE: RPI is retail price index. RPIX is retail price index excluding mortgage interest payments (underlying inflation). PSBR is public sector borrowing requirement (budget deficit) and estimates are for the financial year to April 5.</p>
<p>-- Mike Peacock, London Newsroom +44 171 542 5109</p>
